Concurrency means:

Multiple users accessing or modifying data at the same time.

PK, ye topic 2-Phase Locking (2PL) kaafi heavy lagta hai jab transcript jaisa sunte ho.
Main ise clear mental model + simple timeline example se samjhata hoon taaki “feel” aaye.

1️⃣ Two Phase Locking kya hai?

Database rule:

Transaction do phases me locks handle karega

Phase-1 → Growing Phase
Phase-2 → Shrinking Phase

Phase 1 — Growing Phase

Transaction:

locks acquire kar sakta hai
locks release nahi kar sakta

Example:

lock(A)
lock(B)
lock(C)

Locks badh rahe hain → growing phase.

Phase 2 — Shrinking Phase

Transaction:

locks release karega
new locks acquire nahi kar sakta

Example:

unlock(A)
unlock(B)
unlock(C)

Locks kam ho rahe hain → shrinking phase.

Visual
Locks
  ^
  |        /\
  |       /  \
  |      /    \
  |     /      \
  |____/        \____
       Growing   Shrinking

Isliye naam:

Two Phase Locking
2️⃣ Example (Basic 2PL)

Transaction:

Transfer 10 from A → B

Steps:

lock(A)
lock(B)
update A
update B
unlock(A)
unlock(B)
commit

Phase breakdown:

Growing Phase
--------------
lock(A)
lock(B)

Shrinking Phase
--------------
unlock(A)
unlock(B)

Rule:

Once unlock starts → no new locks allowed
3️⃣ Problem 1 — Deadlock

Deadlock tab hota hai jab transactions ek dusre ka wait karte hain.

Example:

Transaction1:

lock(A)
wait lock(B)

Transaction2:

lock(B)
wait lock(A)

Diagram:

T1 → waiting for B
T2 → waiting for A

Result:

Deadlock

Dono wait karte rahenge forever.

4️⃣ Deadlock Detection
Wait-For Graph

Scheduler graph banata hai:

T1 → T2
T2 → T3
T3 → T1

Agar cycle mil jaye:

Deadlock detected

System ek transaction abort karta hai.

5️⃣ Problem 2 — Cascading Abort

Example:

Transaction1:

lock(A)
update A = 11
unlock(A)

Transaction2:

lock(A)
read A = 11

Ab suppose:

Transaction1 rollback

A wapas:

A = 10

But transaction2 ne:

11 read kiya

Invalid value.

Isliye:

Transaction2 bhi abort karna padega

Isko bolte hain:

Cascading Abort
6️⃣ Types of Two Phase Locking

3 important variants.

1 Basic 2PL
2 Conservative 2PL
3 Strict 2PL
7️⃣ Basic Two Phase Locking

Rules:

Growing phase → acquire locks
Shrinking phase → release locks

But problems:

Deadlock possible
Cascading abort possible
8️⃣ Conservative 2PL

Idea:

Start me hi saare locks le lo

Example:

lock(A)
lock(B)
lock(C)

Agar koi lock available nahi:

transaction start hi nahi hota

Result:

Deadlock impossible

But drawback:

Low concurrency
9️⃣ Strict Two Phase Locking (Most Used)

Rule:

All locks release only at commit

Example:

lock(A)
lock(B)

update A
update B

commit

unlock(A)
unlock(B)

Key difference:

unlock before commit allowed nahi
Benefit
No cascading abort

Because:

koi dirty data read nahi karega
Problem

Still possible:

Deadlock

But DB detect kar leta hai.

🔟 Real Databases kya use karte hain?

Most databases use:

Strict 2PL

Example systems:

MySQL InnoDB
SQL Server
PostgreSQL (with MVCC hybrid)

Because it guarantees:

ACID + consistency
1️⃣1️⃣ Interview Mental Model

Agar interviewer pooche:

What is 2-phase locking?

Answer:

Concurrency control technique
that ensures serializable execution
using two phases:

1 Growing phase → acquire locks
2 Shrinking phase → release locks
1️⃣2️⃣ Real Example (BookMyShow)

Seat booking:

Transaction:

lock(seat)
check status
update seat
commit
unlock

Guarantee:

no two users book same seat